---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Math from '../components/Math.astro';
---

<Base title="Page Turn — Equations" active="Equations" description="Mathematical model for page curl physics.">

  <h1>Equations</h1>
  <p class="subtitle">The mathematical model governing page turn geometry and settle dynamics.</p>

  <h2>1. State machine</h2>

  <p>
    The book's discrete state is an index
    <Math expr="j \in \{-1,\, 0,\, 1,\, \ldots,\, n,\, n{+}1\}" />, where
    <Math expr="n" /> is the number of leaves. Each value of
    <Math expr="j" /> corresponds to a visible spread:
  </p>

  <dl class="def-grid">
    <dt><Math expr="j = -1" /></dt>
    <dd>Front cover closed</dd>
    <dt><Math expr="j = 0" /></dt>
    <dd>First interior spread (front endpaper + page 1)</dd>
    <dt><Math expr="j = k" /></dt>
    <dd>Spread <Math expr="k" />: pages <Math expr="2k" /> and <Math expr="2k{+}1" /></dd>
    <dt><Math expr="j = n" /></dt>
    <dd>Last interior spread (page <Math expr="2n" /> + back endpaper)</dd>
    <dt><Math expr="j = n{+}1" /></dt>
    <dd>Back cover closed</dd>
  </dl>

  <p>
    During a turn, a continuous progress scalar
    <Math expr="p \in [0,1]" /> drives the animation. A forward turn increments
    <Math expr="j" /> when <Math expr="p" /> reaches 1; a reverse turn decrements
    <Math expr="j" /> immediately and animates <Math expr="p" /> from 0 to 1
    (with the angle running in reverse).
  </p>

  <h2>2. Spine angle</h2>

  <p>
    Progress maps to the spine's rotation angle about the Y-axis:
  </p>

  <Math
    expr="\\varphi(p) = \\begin{cases} -\\pi\\, p & \\text{forward turn} \\\\ -\\pi\\,(1 - p) & \\text{reverse turn} \\end{cases}"
    display={true}
    label="1"
  />

  <p>
    The spine sweeps from <Math expr="0" /> (page flat on right) through
    <Math expr="-\\pi/2" /> (vertical) to <Math expr="-\\pi" /> (flat on left).
  </p>

  <h2>3. Per-vertex curl</h2>

  <p>
    The page mesh has 64 segments along its width. Each vertex is parameterized
    by its normalized distance from the spine:
  </p>

  <Math
    expr="t = \\frac{x}{w}, \\quad t \\in [0,\\, 1]"
    display={true}
  />

  <p>
    where <Math expr="x" /> is the vertex's rest position and <Math expr="w" />
    is the page width. The per-vertex rotation angle is:
  </p>

  <Math
    expr="\\phi(t) = \\varphi + A \\cdot t \\cdot \\sin(2\\varphi)"
    display={true}
    label="2"
  />

  <p>
    where <Math expr="A = 0.4" /> is the bend amplitude. The vertex is then
    displaced in the XZ plane:
  </p>

  <Math
    expr="x' = x\\cos\\phi, \\quad z' = -x\\sin\\phi"
    display={true}
    label="3"
  />

  <h3>Why <Math expr="\\sin(2\\varphi)" />?</h3>

  <p>
    The <Math expr="\\sin(2\\varphi)" /> envelope controls how the free edge
    deviates from the spine angle. Its sign matches the direction gravity
    would pull a flexible sheet:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Lift phase</strong> (<Math expr="\\varphi \\in (0, -\\pi/2)" />):
      <Math expr="\\sin(2\\varphi) < 0" />, so the edge angle is more negative
      than the spine — the edge leads, sagging toward the right surface.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Vertical</strong> (<Math expr="\\varphi = -\\pi/2" />):
      <Math expr="\\sin(2\\varphi) = 0" /> — no correction, the page is
      momentarily straight.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Fall phase</strong> (<Math expr="\\varphi \\in (-\\pi/2, -\\pi)" />):
      <Math expr="\\sin(2\\varphi) > 0" />, so the edge angle is less negative
      — the edge lags, sagging toward the left surface.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Together, the page traces a <Math expr="(" /> shape during the lift and a
    <Math expr=")" /> shape during the fall — matching real paper.
  </p>

  <h3>Monotonicity constraint</h3>

  <p>
    The edge must never reverse direction (no "wagging"). The derivative of the
    edge angle with respect to the spine angle is:
  </p>

  <Math
    expr="\\frac{d\\phi_{\\text{edge}}}{d\\varphi} = 1 + 2A\\cos(2\\varphi)"
    display={true}
    label="4"
  />

  <p>
    This is minimized when <Math expr="\\cos(2\\varphi) = -1" />, giving a
    minimum velocity of <Math expr="1 - 2A" />. The constraint is:
  </p>

  <Math
    expr="A < \\tfrac{1}{2} \\implies 1 - 2A > 0"
    display={true}
  />

  <p>
    With <Math expr="A = 0.4" />, the minimum edge velocity is
    <Math expr="0.2 > 0" /> — no stall, no reversal.
  </p>

  <h2>4. Physics settle</h2>

  <p>
    When the user releases a drag, the progress value <Math expr="p" /> is
    governed by a damped gravity model. Each frame:
  </p>

  <Math
    expr="\\dot{v} = \\text{dir} \\cdot G - D \\cdot v"
    display={true}
    label="5"
  />

  <Math
    expr="p_{n+1} = \\operatorname{clamp}\\!\\left(p_n + v \\cdot \\Delta t,\\; 0,\\; 1\\right)"
    display={true}
    label="6"
  />

  <p>
    where:
  </p>

  <dl class="def-grid">
    <dt><Math expr="G = 5.0" /></dt>
    <dd>Gravitational acceleration (progress units/s²)</dd>
    <dt><Math expr="D = 6.5" /></dt>
    <dd>Drag coefficient (velocity damping)</dd>
    <dt><Math expr="\\text{dir}" /></dt>
    <dd><Math expr="+1" /> if settling forward, <Math expr="-1" /> if settling back</dd>
    <dt><Math expr="\\Delta t" /></dt>
    <dd>Frame timestep (<Math expr="1/60" /> s)</dd>
  </dl>

  <p>
    The settle target is chosen by threshold: if the drag ended past
    <Math expr="p \\geq 0.5" />, the page completes; otherwise it snaps back.
    Velocity is seeded with the drag momentum but clamped to a minimum of
    <Math expr="|v_0| \\geq 0.8" /> to prevent the page from stalling at the
    midpoint (where the bend envelope is also zero).
  </p>

  <h2>5. Timed animation</h2>

  <p>
    Button and keyboard turns use linear progress over a fixed duration:
  </p>

  <Math
    expr="p(t) = \\frac{t}{T}, \\quad T = 1.2\\text{ s}"
    display={true}
    label="7"
  />

  <h2>6. Crease shadow</h2>

  <p>
    A thin line at the spine fades in during a turn. Its opacity follows a
    bell curve peaking at mid-turn:
  </p>

  <Math
    expr="\\alpha_{\\text{crease}} = \\sin(\\pi\\, p)"
    display={true}
    label="8"
  />

  <p>
    The line itself is a tight Gaussian across the strip width:
  </p>

  <Math
    expr="\\text{shadow}(d) = e^{-80\\, d^2}"
    display={true}
  />

  <p>
    where <Math expr="d \\in [0,1]" /> is the normalized distance from the
    strip center.
  </p>

  <h2>7. GLSL implementation</h2>

  <p>
    The vertex shader implements equations (2) and (3) directly:
  </p>

<pre><code>float t = pos.x / uPageWidth;
float phi = uAngle + uBendAmount * t * sin(2.0 * uAngle);

float origX = pos.x;
pos.x =  origX * cos(phi);
pos.z = -origX * sin(phi);</code></pre>

  <p>
    The fragment shader uses <code>gl_FrontFacing</code> to select between the
    front and back textures, mirroring the U coordinate for the back face:
  </p>

<pre><code>if (gl_FrontFacing) &#123;
  gl_FragColor = texture2D(frontTexture, vUv);
&#125; else &#123;
  gl_FragColor = texture2D(backTexture, vec2(1.0 - vUv.x, vUv.y));
&#125;</code></pre>

</Base>
